<b>Francis James Braidwood</b> was a successful cabinetmaker in [[Edinburgh|Edinburgh]] and co-owner of the upholstery company <i>Braidwood & Bruce</i>. He was the father of the famous firefighter [[James Braidwood|James_Braidwood]] and was said to be the first person in Edinburgh to wear shoelaces.[f] He was the four-times-great-grandfather of [[Mary MacDonald|Mary_MacDonald]].

# Early Life

Francis was born around 1752 to [[William Braidwood|William_Braidwood]], a candlemaker.[j][l] He was apprenticed to cabinet-making.[b] He moved to London as a young man.[m]


# Career

Francis returned to Edinburgh some time around 1775. At the time, he was a joiner, cabinet-maker, upholsterer and undertaker. From London he brought with him a wide assortment of woods that would allow him to produce inlaid furniture. He moved into a Luckenbooths warehouse formerly owned by Young and Trotter, two well-known upholsterers that were operating in Edinburgh.[m]

With his business partner Alexander Bruce, Francis ran an upholstery shop <i>Braidwood & Bruce</i> at South Bridge Street from 1784 to 1804.[d] The company was not heard of after 1805.[e] In 1806, the warehouse was acquired by William Henderson.[n] 

On 10 November 1807, at around three or four o'clock in the morning, a fire was discovered at Francis's workshop at the Pleasance, near the head of Arthur's Seat. Intervention could not be made on time and so the fire consumed the workshop.[f][b]

Francis was a successful upholsterer who hired workers. In around the year 1810, Francis's workers went on strike to demand higher wages.[c]

A notice appeared in the Caledonian Mercury on 4 April 1814 announcing the bankruptcy three days earlier of an upholsterers company, Braidwood and Giles, which appears to have been owned by Francis.[i]

Francis removed himself to Adam Square. He was a captain of the Edinburgh Volunteers.[b]

After much success working in upholstery, Francis decided to enter into quarry work, and contracted for buildings in both Scotland and England.[b] Francis constructed King's College Bridge at the University of Cambridge. Despite finding a lot of success as an upholsterer, he was not successful in this new industry.

