# Family

Francis had at least one brother — [[William|William_Braidwood_1]] — and at least one sister.

In 1796, his sister married Forrest Alexander. Francis and William viewed this marriage with contempt due to Forrest's position as a low shoemaker. Knowing of their view of themselves as "some pumkins", Forrest was well aware of their attitude towards him. Forrest went on to found the Commercial Bank of Scotland, a predecessor to the Royal Bank of Scotland.[h] Despite any scorn that at some point appears to have existed, Francis did go on to co-operate with his new brother-in-law in professional matters.

On 23 July 1775, Francis married Janet Mitchell at Tolbooth Church. Janet was the daughter of Andrew Mitchell, a brewer in the south of Leith.[g]


# Personal Life

Francis was elected Deacon of the Wrights in 1795 and Deacon Convener the following year.[b]

He was a keen golfer and the chaplain of the Edinburgh Burgess Golfing Club. He was also a member of the <i>Spendthrift Club</i>, a group of men who enjoyed walking after church services. The name was given to them in reference to their frugalness.[b]


# Death

Francis died 19 December 1828 in Edinburgh.[a] He left two daughters and two sons. His two daughters remained in Edinburgh, while James settled in London, and William in the United States.[b]

Other notes

The home Francis moved to in Adam Square went on at some point after him to be occupied by Messrs Dalgleish and Forrest.[b]


